            <p>As well as modifying verbs, prefixes are often added to nouns with a smiliar effect. So, the noun
                <em>un-weder</em> means 'bad weather'
                and the noun <em>utscytan</em> (from <em>scyt - defacate</em> + prefix 'ut') gives a very descriptive
                noun
                for diarrhoea.
                One thing to bear in mind with the prefix <strong>ge-</strong>, which you've already come across in the
                past
                participles section of this
                module, is that it has a similar 'perfective' effect when placed in front of the participle - in the
                sense
                that it indicates a completed
                action - so the past participle of '<em>hieran - to hear</em>' may be written as <em>hiered -
                    heard</em>, or
                as <em>gehiered</em>, with
                the prefix <strong>ge-</strong> reinforcing its completedness.</p>
